<asp:Content ID="Content2" ContentPlaceHolderID="MainContent" runat="server">
   
    <p1>
    The FIRST Tech Challenge (FTC) is an international robotics program designed for middle and high school students who are interested in technology and engineering.
In FTC, students work together in teams to design, build, and program a competition robot.
Each season, FIRST releases a new game with specific tasks that the robot must complete.
Teams must carefully study the rules to understand how points are scored.
Using metal parts, motors, sensors, and controllers, students build a robot that fits strict size limits.
Programming plays a major role in FTC and is usually done using Java or block-based tools.
Students learn how software and hardware work together.
Problem solving is a constant part of the process as robots rarely work perfectly on the first try.
Teams test, fail, redesign, and improve throughout the season.
Strategy is just as important as building skill.
Teams must decide which tasks are worth focusing on during matches.
FTC competitions are held in a friendly and supportive environment.
Teams compete in alliances, meaning cooperation is essential.
Judging is based not only on robot performance but also on teamwork and communication.
Teams are required to keep an engineering notebook.
This notebook documents ideas, designs, and improvements made over time.
FTC teaches students how to plan long-term projects.
Time management becomes an important skill during the season.
Students gain experience working under pressure during competitions.
Mentors guide students without doing the work for them.
This helps students develop independence and responsibility.
FTC emphasizes values such as Gracious Professionalism and respect.
Creativity is encouraged in both robot design and problem solving.
Students learn technical skills in mechanics, electronics, and coding.
They also develop soft skills like leadership and teamwork.
FTC prepares students for future studies in STEM fields.
Participants gain confidence in their abilities.
The program encourages curiosity and innovation.
Students meet others who share similar interests.
Overall, FTC provides a strong and balanced robotics experience.
    </p1>
    <h1>how to make your own team</h1>
    <p1>Creating an FTC team begins with bringing together students who are interested in robotics and technology.
A successful team includes members who are willing to learn and work together.
The next important step is finding an adult mentor or coach.
Mentors help guide the team and provide support throughout the season.
Once the team is formed, it must register on the official FIRST website.
Registration provides the team with a unique team number.
Choosing a team name helps build identity and motivation.
After registering, the team should find a suitable workspace.
This space should be safe and large enough for building and testing.
Teams then need to gather basic tools and robot parts.
Funding is required to cover equipment and competition fees.
Teams often raise money through sponsorships and fundraising activities.
Planning is a key part of starting strong.
Students should read the game manual as soon as it is released.
Understanding the rules early helps avoid mistakes later.
The team should discuss strategies before building the robot.
Design ideas can be sketched and tested with prototypes.
Building and programming should happen at the same time.
Testing regularly helps improve performance.
Teams must document their work in an engineering notebook.
Clear communication helps everyone stay organized.
Assigning roles can make the team more efficient.
Holding regular meetings keeps progress on track.
Problems should be solved together as a team.
Mistakes are part of the learning process.
Students should review what worked and what did not.
Practicing before competitions builds confidence.
Respect and teamwork are essential at all times.
Competitions provide valuable experience and feedback.
Creating an FTC team helps students grow both technically and personally.</p1>
